            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Madison Clarke\u2019s story began not in the fog-laced hills of San Francisco, but under the perpetually gray skies of a Portland suburb. Raised by an architect father and a high school English teacher mother, she grew up in a home that valued both structured design and creative expression. This duality defined her path. She pursued an undergraduate degree in psychology at the University of Washington, fascinated by the \"why\" behind human behavior. Her turning point was a summer internship at a small Seattle startup, where she saw firsthand how confusing software could frustrate users. It was there she discovered her calling: bridging the gap between human intuition and digital interfaces.\n\nThis newfound passion led her to Carnegie Mellon\u2019s prestigious Human-Computer Interaction program. Armed with her master's degree, she was recruited by a leading enterprise software company in San Francisco. As a Product Manager, Madison now spends her days translating complex user research into tangible product roadmaps, a role that perfectly marries her empathy with her analytical mind.\n\nHer life is centered in Hayes Valley, a neighborhood whose vibrant, boutique-filled streets feel a world away from her SoMa office. Each morning, she grabs an oat latte from a local caf\u00e9 before hopping on the Muni for her 2.5-mile commute. Evenings are for unwinding at a climbing gym with colleagues or trying a new restaurant in The Mission. Having recently ended a long-term relationship, Madison is channeling her energy into her career and friendships, building a chosen family in the city.\n\nSan Francisco, for Madison, is more than just a career stepping stone; it's a crucible for self-discovery. While she dreams of eventually leading a product division dedicated to ethical tech, her more immediate hope is to feel truly settled. She wants to trade weekend hikes in Marin for finding a community pottery class, to build connections that aren't tied to a job title, and to finally make this transient city feel like a permanent home."
